President Uhuru Kenyatta has announced various mitigation measures that his government will introduce aimed at lessening the impact of the coronavirus pandemic on businesses and individuals. The Covid-19 disease, which originated in China, has spread in over 184 countries and territories around the world and infected more than 400,000 people. Kenya has confirmed three more cases on Wednesday, taking the total to 28. The country also reported its first case in which a patient has fully recovered. Here are some of the highlights from the President’s speech on Wednesday at State House, Nairobi: Central Bank measures Curfew The President also urged Kenyans to limit the spread of the virus through basic changes in individual behaviour and hygiene. -            wash hands frequently with hand sanitisers or soap and water for at least 20 seconds; -            cover our nose and mouth when coughing and sneezing with tissue or flexed elbow; -            avoid close contact with anyone with cold or flu-like symptoms. "These measures will slow the spread and ease the effects of COVID-19 on our nation, and allow our health care system and our first responders to most effectively deal with the pandemic," he added. 